Living specimens purple red, parapodia with golden chaetae (
Fig. 2A, B
). Body oval and flattened, tapering slightly anteriorly and more so posteriorly; parapodia almost as long as trunk width (
Fig. 2A–J
). Eleven pairs of elytra, attached to prominent elytrophores located on segments 2, 4, 5, 7, and alternate segments to 21, completely covering dorsum (
Fig. 2A
); thick and stiff, round to subreniform, with thickened bulbous projections along posterior border (
Figs 2A
; 3G–L); micro- and macropapillae on surface, filiform to oval, mainly scattered in posterior part (
Fig. 3J–L
), extending anteriorly in small elytra (
Fig. 3L
), detached in larger elytra (
Fig. 3G, H, I
). Elytrophores large and prominent (
Figs 2C
; 3A). Dorsal cirri present on segments lacking elytra, with cirrophores cylindrical, bulbous basally, attached to posterodorsal sides of notopodia; styles with long slender tips, extending beyond tips of chaetae (
Fig. 4B, D
). Dorsal tubercles nodular (
Figs 2C
; 3A; 4B).

Prostomium wider than long, deeply bilobed, cephalic peaks (anterior lobes) triangular with delicate frontal filaments (
Fig. 2E–J
; frontal filaments detached in 
holotype
). Ceratophore of median antenna cylindrical, inserted in anterior notch; style subulate with a long terminal filament (
Fig. 3A
). Palps stout, tapered with slender tips (
Fig. 3A, B
; right palp detached in 
holotype
). Lateral antennae and eyes absent. Tentacular segment (peristomium) achaetous, dorsally invisible, ventrally forming bilobed facial tubercle and lips surrounding mouth (
Fig. 3B
). Tentaculophores cylindrical, inserted laterally to prostomium; two pairs of tentacular cirri with long slender tips, slightly shorter than palps, dorsal pair much longer than ventral pair (
Fig. 3B
).

Biramous parapodia well developed, notopodia slightly shorter than neuropodia except for segment 2 (
Fig. 4A–D
). Notopodia cylindrical with a projecting acicular lobe on lower side and numerous notochaetae forming a radiating bundle. Notochaetae golden, much stouter than neurochaetae, short to longer (
Fig. 4A–D
), straight or slightly curved with bare blunt tips, smooth or serrated with widely spaced spines along curved side (
Fig. 4E–G
). Neuropodia including a conical prechaetal lobe with a projecting acicular process, and a short rounded postchaetal lobe (
Fig. 4A–D
). Neurochaetae numerous, long and slender, forming a fan-shaped bundle; supra-acicular neurochaetae slender, distal spinous region with two rows of long, widely spaced spines along borders (
Fig. 4H, J
), and proximal spinous region with two rows of transverse teeth (
Fig. 4J
); subacicular neurochaetae stouter than supra-acicular ones, distal spinous region knife-like with minute, close-set spines along curved side, and slightly hooked bare tips (
Fig. 4H
), proximal spinous region with a row of transverse teeth (

Fig. 
4I

). Ventral cirri short, tapered, attached on middle of neuropodia (
Fig. 4B–D
).

Pygidium small, rectangular, with a pair of slender anal cirri (
Fig. 3F
). Seven out of 
13 specimens
with two pairs of long ventral papillae (containing a whitish secretion) on segments 11 and 12 (
Fig. 2
); the first pair distally dichotomous (
Fig. 3C, D
).
